Last Opening Night for 2022
.
.
.
#ausballet #romeoandjuliet #ballerinasofig #ballerina #ballet #dancer #openingnight #onstage

That’s me signing off for 2022. I’m not injured, or sick, just taking some time away from touring for the first time in 21 years. I’ve been so fortunate to become a Mum and remain a ballerina. I’ve been on the road with Willow since she was 4 months old and she has toured everywhere with Jarryd and myself since. We’ve taken her to China, London, Japan and all over Australia and it’s been so wonderful having her right by our sides and sharing in this crazy life we live. But unfortunately touring life and a school-age child brings many challenges. Also a lot of heartache, tears, I’m riddled with guilt, stress and worry. 6.5 weeks away from her is not doable and nor is 6.5 weeks out of school, so we took her out for 2 weeks to be all together in Sydney, she’s home with my Mum for 2 weeks and then Phoenix and myself will head home for the remainder of the Sydney season and Jarryd will remain here by himself for the final 2.5 weeks. It’s a decision that wasn’t easily made and one that weighed heavily on me because I am so committed to my job and of course I considered the impact it would have on my colleagues for the shows I would miss. I will also miss the start of rehearsals for our 23’ season and be behind on learning repertoire but it’s the decision I have made and feel good about and know it’s where I need to be. It’s a selfish career and for the first time in 8 years of touring with babies I’m putting my babies and what we/I need first. I’ll be back at Aus Ballet HQ in Melbs swinging a leg and doing some things until the year is finished and while my babies are at school, so stay tuned X 

#mylittleloves #fillingmycup #signingoff

#tututuesday coming to you from one of my favourite moments over the last 2 years. Dancing this pas de deux with @tykingwall at our Summertime performances at Margaret Court Arena
.
Initially when we started to rehearse I was filled with so much doubt that I could even take on a role like this one. There have been very few times over my career that I have been cast and given opportunities like this. We had just come off the back of Covid and prior to that I had only briefly returned to the stage after having Phoenix. So it was all very overwhelming and mentally I was not feeling very strong. But, weeks of rehearsals and an amazing partner and finding my mojo once again, I felt so calm and ready to get it to stage and perform. There’s not been many times where I have felt like this, like a ballerina but I’ve never felt so calm and felt more at home on stage
.
.
.

Big day for us. Actually, it’s been a big week leading up to Willow heading home today. A week filled with lots of emotions for all of us. It’s never easy knowing that she’s heading back to Melbourne and we will be apart for the next 3 weeks

Truly grateful to my Mum for being the one to make this all work. It’s all only possible because my Mum moves her life to Melbourne for weeks to allow Willow to be a kid and head to school and for both Jarryd and I to continue doing what we love

It will continue to be an emotional few weeks with Phoenix absolutely lost without Willow and all of us missing her. Thank god for FaceTime, but also sometimes it just sucks. I don’t like to wish time away but when I’m on tour for 7 weeks and away from my little girl, I absolutely do and I can’t wait for it to be over

Special guests in the house over the weekend 🫶🏻
.
First photo is with one of my first ballet teachers. @kezza29771 flew up to Sydney with her Mum, Marg, to be in the audience for Opening Night. I remember so many things from our time together. Like, practising my neo solo to Michael Jackson’s ‘Ben’ in her shed to my Mum and Kerri telling me I would be the ‘Wicked Queen’ for a character solo and me bawling my eyes out 🤣 Fun fact - my Mum would drive me to competitions, I would be all ready to perform, hair, make up and costume on (the one I remember was ‘Little red riding hood’ character solo) I would be standing in the wings, it’s my turn, and I just wouldn’t go on. No one could get me out there, so we would get in the car and drive all the way back home. It happened numerous times until Kerri took me to the local town hall where she had created a stage and space, got me comfortable and got me out there. I never looked back!! Wild for her to see me on Friday night at the Sydney Opera House. Who would have thought!

2023
You were a bit of everything. Good and bad, highs and lows. Starting my working year filled with so much self-doubt but then huge decisions were made. I found a sense of calm again in what felt like the first time in forever. My mind became clear and I found myself living in the moment and soaking it all in, again in what felt like the first time in forever. It was reflective with floods of tears but moments of feeling so proud of myself. I turned 40. I travelled with my love to one of my favourite places in the world, London and performed at the Royal Opera House in what will forever be some of the most beautiful and proudest moments of my career. We lost our first pet. My baby girl turned 9 and my baby boy 4. Willow started ballet and performed for the first time on stage with lights and an audience twice during the year. She also nailed her drum performance and I could be there!! Phoenix finished Daycare. I retired from the stage after 22 years with the Australian Ballet and will forever be grateful for it all. We lost our beautiful Special Nanny 💔 
.
The end of a huge chapter of my life but here’s to the next and all it has to offer. More time with family and friends, celebrating life, birthdays and milestones, more date nights and little getaways with my little family. Saying yes, but also saying no. Liking myself a little more. Continuing to find calm, being less stressed and anxious. So much to look forward to! Forever grateful for my love and my babies. 2024, I’m excited for you!
#2023recap
